# Project Context

DataSense is an AI-powered chat interface for querying open datasets published on
data.gov.in. Next.js (App Router) + TypeScript, Groq LLM for generating responses.
Users sign in with Google or email/password and get persisted chat history. Users
are not limited to a fixed list of datasets — they can point the app at any
resource on data.gov.in by pasting its page URL or resource ID.

# Tech Stack

- Next.js (App Router), TypeScript (strict mode)
- Groq LLM API — calls happen server-side only, never from client components
- data.gov.in REST API — one API key (tied to the account, not the dataset) works
  for fetching ANY resource by `resource_id` (UUID). There is no public catalog
  search API on data.gov.in — resource IDs can only be obtained by a human finding
  a dataset's page and either reading the ID off it directly, or the server
  scraping that one page for UUID candidates and testing them.
- Auth.js v5 (`next-auth`) — Google OAuth AND a Credentials (email/password)
  provider. Session strategy is JWT (required for Credentials).
- bcryptjs for hashing passwords.
- MongoDB via **Mongoose** (`mongoose` package) — all collections are defined as
  Mongoose models in `src/models/`. Do NOT use the native `mongodb` driver directly
  or `@auth/mongodb-adapter`. Auth.js uses a custom Mongoose-based adapter or the
  Credentials provider directly.
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui (Radix primitives) for UI
- Zod for server env validation and API request body validation — schemas live in
  `src/schemas/`.

# Database — Mongoose Models (src/models/)

All MongoDB access goes through Mongoose models. One file per model, PascalCase
filename matching the model name. Each model file exports:
  1. A TypeScript interface for the document (e.g. `IUser`)
  2. A Mongoose Schema
  3. The compiled Model (with the Next.js hot-reload guard pattern:
     `mongoose.models.User || mongoose.model<IUser>('User', UserSchema)`)

Models:

- `src/models/User.ts`
  Fields: name, email (unique, required), password (optional — absent for Google
  sign-in users), image, emailVerified, createdAt, updatedAt.
  The `password` field is optional because Google OAuth users won't have one.

- `src/models/Conversation.ts`
  Fields: userId (ref: 'User'), title, datasetId (the resource_id string),
  datasetTitle, createdAt, updatedAt.

- `src/models/Message.ts`
  Fields: conversationId (ref: 'Conversation'), role ('user' | 'assistant'),
  content, createdAt.

- `src/models/Dataset.ts`
  Fields: resourceId (unique, the UUID), title, portalUrl, fields (array of
  field name strings), resolvedAt, addedByUserId (ref: 'User').
  This is a shared cache across all users — one user resolving a dataset benefits
  everyone.

# Project Structure

- `src/models/` — Mongoose models (User, Conversation, Message, Dataset).
- `src/schemas/` — Zod schemas for API request validation (registerSchema,
  signInSchema, chatRequestSchema, createConversationSchema, datasetResolveSchema).
- `src/lib/mongoose.ts` — cached Mongoose connection helper (use this in every
  server-side file that needs the DB — do not open new connections per request).
- `src/app/api/chat/route.ts` — Groq streaming chat handler.
- `src/app/api/conversations/route.ts` — list + create conversations.
- `src/app/api/conversations/[id]/route.ts` — get + delete one conversation.
- `src/app/api/datasets/route.ts` — list resolved datasets from Dataset model.
- `src/app/api/datasets/resolve/route.ts` — resolve a pasted URL or resource_id.
- `src/app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts` — Auth.js handler.
- `src/app/api/auth/register/route.ts` — email/password signup.
- `src/app/chat/` and `src/app/chat/[id]/` — chat pages.
- `src/components/datasense/` — chat UI components.
- `src/components/marketing/` — logged-out landing page.
- `src/components/providers/` — ThemeProvider, AppProviders.
- `src/hooks/` — useChat, useConversations.
- `src/lib/ai/` — chat-service.ts, prompts.ts.
- `src/lib/conversations/` — service.ts (uses Mongoose models), stream.ts, types.ts.
- `src/lib/data-gov-in/` — API client + resolve.ts.
- `src/lib/api-response.ts` — shared jsonError() and jsonOk() helpers.
- `src/lib/env.ts` — Zod-validated server env.
- `src/lib/errors.ts` — AppError class.
- `src/auth.config.ts` — Edge-safe config for middleware.ts (Google provider,
  callbacks, pages). Must NEVER import mongoose, bcrypt, or anything Node-only.
- `src/auth.ts` — full config: spreads authConfig, adds Credentials provider
  (authorize() uses Mongoose User model + bcrypt.compare — both Node-only, so
  this file must never be imported in middleware.ts).
- `src/middleware.ts` — protects /chat/:path*, imports from src/auth.config.ts only.
- `src/types/next-auth.d.ts` — extends Session.user with id.

# Mongoose Connection Pattern

src/lib/mongoose.ts must use the standard Next.js cached connection pattern:

```typescript
import mongoose from 'mongoose';

const MONGODB_URI = process.env.MONGODB_URI!;
let cached = global.mongoose || { conn: null, promise: null };

export async function connectDB() {
  if (cached.conn) return cached.conn;
  if (!cached.promise) {
    cached.promise = mongoose.connect(MONGODB_URI).then(m => m);
  }
  cached.conn = await cached.promise;
  return cached.conn;
}
```

Every server-side function that touches the DB calls `await connectDB()` at the top.
Never open a second connection. Never call mongoose.connect() outside this helper.

# Conventions

- Server Components by default. Add "use client" only when needed.
- All Groq, data.gov.in, and database calls in route.ts handlers or src/lib/ —
  never in client components.
- Every API route checks the session via auth() first and returns 401 if missing.
  Never trust a client-supplied user id.
- API routes return { error: string, code?: string } via jsonError() from
  src/lib/api-response.ts. Don't redefine it locally.
- Request bodies validated with Zod schemas from src/schemas/.
- Use async/await, not .then() chains.
- Keep route handlers thin — logic belongs in src/lib/.
- Naming: PascalCase for components and Mongoose models, camelCase for
  functions/variables.

# Dataset Resolution

- Datasets are identified by a raw resource_id (UUID string), not a hardcoded enum.
- Users add a dataset by pasting a data.gov.in page URL or a raw resource_id.
- URL flow: fetch that one page's HTML, regex-extract UUID candidates, test each
  against api.data.gov.in/resource/{id}?limit=1 until one returns records.
- Resource ID flow: directly call api.data.gov.in/resource/{id}?limit=1.
- Resolved datasets are upserted into the Dataset model (shared cache).
- There is NO keyword search across datasets — data.gov.in has no such API.

# Data & Cost Awareness

- One API key for all resource_ids — don't gate access behind a hardcoded list.
- LLM prompts trim dataset JSON and cap chat history — keep new code consistent.
- Dataset resolution (URL scraping) should happen once per dataset (cached in
  Dataset model), never on every chat message.

# Avoid

- Don't use the native mongodb driver directly — all DB access goes through Mongoose.
- Don't add @auth/mongodb-adapter — not needed when using Mongoose + Credentials.
- Don't add Express or a separate backend.
- Don't import src/auth.ts into middleware.ts — use src/auth.config.ts only.
- Don't assume Google + email/password on the same email auto-link accounts.
- Never log or return the password hash to the client.
- Don't hardcode API keys, resource_ids, model names, or MONGODB_URI.
- Don't build a "search all datasets" feature — data.gov.in has no such API.
- Don't re-add a fixed DatasetId enum — resource IDs are arbitrary UUID strings.
- Don't open duplicate Mongoose connections — always use connectDB() from
  src/lib/mongoose.ts.

# When Unsure

- If a refactor changes an API route's response shape or headers, check
  useChat.ts and useConversations.ts first — they parse exact field names.
- If something requires a new MongoDB collection, flag it and ask before adding
  a new model.
- Ask before generating code if the location for new logic is ambiguous.
